rts with street children and out-of-school village girls. Her in-depth ethnographic study reveals how global medical aid fails to "save" these children according to its stated aims, and often maintains—or produces new—social disparities in children's lives. Foregrounding vulnerable children's responses to medical aid, Sweis moves past the unquestioned benevolence of global health to demonstrate how children must manage their own bodies and lives in the absence of adult care. With this book, she challenges readers to engage with the question of what medical caregivers and donors alike gain from such global humanitarian transactions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aChild health serviceszEgypt. 0aChild health services-Egypt. 0aChildrenxHealth and hygienezEgypt. 0aChildren-Health and hygiene-Egypt. 0aMedical assistancezEgypt. 0aMedical assistance-Egypt. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Disease & Health Issues.2bisacsh  aAnthropology.  aChildren.  aEgypt.  aGender.  aGlobal health.  aInternational aid.  aMedical Humanitarianis.  aMedical aid.  aStreet Children.  aVillage girls.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2021 Englishz978311075418608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2021z9783110753967oZDB-23-DSL08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073914540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150362864940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503628649423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503628649/original  a978-3-11-073914-5  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-075400-1  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishb